This KQL query identifies all devices where Sensor Data Collection is NOT compliant. These devices are failing to collect or send critical Defender XDR telemetry such as process events, network events, system signals, and behavioral indicators.
SensorDataCollection is one of the most important Defender configuration checks because it determines whether a device is providing the data that Microsoft Defender XDR and Microsoft Sentinel rely on for threat detection, correlation, and investigation.

✅ How This KQL Helps SOC & Security Teams
1. Reveals “Blind Spots” in the Environment
Devices with Sensor Data Collection disabled or broken become invisible to XDR and Sentinel for many key signals.
This query helps the SOC immediately see which endpoints represent visibility gaps.

2. Improves Detection Coverage
If a device is not collecting telemetry, it won’t trigger behavioral detections, making it easier for threats to hide.
This query allows the SOC to prioritize remediation to restore full detection capability.

3. Ensures Investigations Are Complete
When the SOC opens an incident, missing telemetry results in:

No process tree
No lateral movement mapping
Missing network data
No behavioral evidence

This query highlights the devices that would cause incomplete or misleading investigations.

4. Enables Proactive Health Monitoring
The SOC can run this regularly to:

A-Maintain device telemetry health
B-Detect configuration drift
C-Catch onboarding failures early
D-Ensure endpoint compliance before incidents happen


5. Supports Cross‑Correlation With Alerts
By joining this dataset with AlertInfo, DeviceEvents, or Sentinel incidents, you can quickly find:

Alerts that happened on devices with broken telemetry
Suspicious activity where the sensor was not working

This is crucial for validating whether the SOC has the full picture.

✅ So what is ActionType then?
The ActionType column is NOT “missing telemetry.”
Instead:
✔ ActionType = the security events that DID get collected
Examples:

ProcessCreation
NetworkConnection
FileCreated
MalwareDetected
SmartScreenUrlWarning
etc.

ActionType shows the telemetry that is still coming in, even if the sensor is partially broken.

❗ So what telemetry is the device missing?
When IsCompliant = false, you are missing some or many of the following:

Process events
Network flow events
Behavior events
Identity signals
EDR correlation data
Sensor‑level artifacts used for detection

BUT Defender does not provide a list of “exactly which telemetry is missing.”
Instead, SCID‑2001 tells you:

“This device is not sending all the telemetry required for full detection & investigation.”

The SOC knows:
➡️ Investigation results may be incomplete
➡️ Important events may not appear
➡️ Some ActionTypes will be missing entirely

The KQL shows the ActionTypes that DID arrive, This tells you:

“Even though the sensor is NOT OK, here are the last known events we received for that device.”

It does NOT mean these are the missing events — these are the events you DO have.


1️⃣ MissingProcess
✔ Included because process creation is the #1 telemetry for detecting:

Malware execution
LOLBins (PowerShell, WMI, cmd.exe)
Persistence techniques
Ransomware behavior

If you don’t have process telemetry → you are blind to execution.

2️⃣ MissingNetwork
✔ Included because network flow telemetry detects:

C2 (command‑and‑control) callbacks
Lateral movement
Data exfiltration
Port scanning / probing

If network events are missing → you cannot catch C2 or exfil.

3️⃣ MissingFile
✔ Included because file telemetry identifies:

Malware dropping files
VBA payloads
Ransomware encryption
Suspicious file writes

File events = evidence of malicious activity at rest.

4️⃣ MissingLogon
✔ Included because logon telemetry is critical for:

Account takeover
RDP brute force
Pass‑the‑Hash
Privilege escalation

If logon data is missing → identity-based attacks become invisible.

5️⃣ MissingHeartbeat (DeviceInfo)
✔ Included because Heartbeat =
“Is the device alive and reporting to Defender?”
This ensures:

Defender sensor is connected
Device has checked in recently
You are not looking at a stale / dead endpoint

If Heartbeat is missing → the device might be offline or broken.
___________________________________________________

let TimeRange = 30d;
// === 1) Devices where Sensor Data Collection is NOT OK===
let sensorBad =
    DeviceTvmSecureConfigurationAssessment
    | where Timestamp > ago(TimeRange)
    | where ConfigurationId == "scid-2001"
    | summarize arg_max(Timestamp, *) by DeviceId
    | where IsCompliant == false
    | project DeviceId, DeviceName, IsCompliant;
let proc =
    DeviceProcessEvents
    | where Timestamp > ago(TimeRange)
    | summarize hasProcess = count() by DeviceId;
let net =
    DeviceNetworkEvents
    | where Timestamp > ago(TimeRange)
    | summarize hasNetwork = count() by DeviceId;
let file =
    DeviceFileEvents
    | where Timestamp > ago(TimeRange)
    | summarize hasFile = count() by DeviceId;
let logon =
    DeviceLogonEvents
    | where Timestamp > ago(TimeRange)
    | summarize hasLogon = count() by DeviceId;
let reg =
    DeviceRegistryEvents
    | where Timestamp > ago(TimeRange)
    | summarize hasRegistry = count() by DeviceId;
let img =
    DeviceImageLoadEvents
    | where Timestamp > ago(TimeRange)
    | summarize hasImageLoad = count() by DeviceId;
let dns =
    DeviceNetworkInfo
    | where Timestamp > ago(TimeRange)
    | summarize hasDNS = count() by DeviceId;
let hb_devices =
    DeviceInfo
    | where Timestamp > ago(TimeRange)
    | summarize hasHeartbeat = count() by DeviceId;
sensorBad
| join kind=leftouter proc on DeviceId
| join kind=leftouter net on DeviceId
| join kind=leftouter file on DeviceId
| join kind=leftouter logon on DeviceId
| join kind=leftouter reg on DeviceId
| join kind=leftouter img on DeviceId
| join kind=leftouter dns on DeviceId
| join kind=leftouter hb_devices on DeviceId
| extend
    MissingProcess     = iff(coalesce(tolong(hasProcess), 0) == 0, "Missing", "OK"),
    MissingNetwork     = iff(coalesce(tolong(hasNetwork), 0) == 0, "Missing", "OK"),
    MissingFile        = iff(coalesce(tolong(hasFile), 0) == 0, "Missing", "OK"),
    MissingLogon       = iff(coalesce(tolong(hasLogon), 0) == 0, "Missing", "OK"),
    MissingRegistry    = iff(coalesce(tolong(hasRegistry), 0) == 0, "Missing", "OK"),
    MissingImageLoad   = iff(coalesce(tolong(hasImageLoad), 0) == 0, "Missing", "OK"),
    MissingDNS         = iff(coalesce(tolong(hasDNS), 0) == 0, "Missing", "OK"),
    MissingHeartbeat   = iff(coalesce(tolong(hasHeartbeat), 0) == 0, "Missing", "OK")
| project DeviceName, DeviceId, IsCompliant,
          MissingProcess, MissingNetwork, MissingFile, MissingLogon,
          MissingRegistry, MissingImageLoad, MissingDNS, MissingHeartbeat
| sort by DeviceName asc
